This problem is a testing of your "sorting" skills. Especially with ur understanding of counting sort and quicksort
**2-pass** is essentially counting sort [geeksforgeeks video tutorial for counting sort](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7zuGmKfUt7s&feature=youtu.be)
**1-pass**  is essentially the 3-way quick partition method in quicksort. check this [gret video demo](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WBFzOYJ5ybM&t=177s) from Professor Robert Sedgewick
```
    //-------------  SOLUTION 1: 2 SCANs ----------------//
    // counting sort
    public void sortColors(int[] A) {
        // count
        int[] counts = new int[3];
        for (int i: A) {
            counts[i]++;
        }
        // fill
        for (int i = 0; i < A.length; i++) {
            if (i < counts[0]) {
                A[i] = 0;
            } else if (i < counts[0] + counts[1]) {
                A[i] = 1;
            } else {
                A[i] = 2;
            }
        }
    }
```



```
quicksort 3-way partition
+------+---------+-------------+-------+
|  <p  |  =p     |  unseen .  |   > p  |
+------+---------+------------+-------+
        ↑          ↑           ↑
        lt         i            gt 
lt: 1st elem == pivot
i:  1st unseen elem
gt: last unseen elem
```
```
    //-------------  SOLUTION 2: 1 SCAN ----------------//
    // 3-way partition used in quick sort
    public void sortColors(int[] nums) {
        int lt = 0, i = 0, gt = nums.length - 1;
        while (i <= gt) {
            if (nums[i] == 0) {
                swap(nums, lt++, i++);
            } else if (nums[i] == 2) {
                swap(nums, i, gt--);
            } else { // nums[i] == 1
                i++;
            }
        }
    }
    private void swap(int[] nums, int p1, int p2) {
        int temp = nums[p1];
        nums[p1] = nums[p2];
        nums[p2] = temp;
    }

