# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Intution here is do it in a single pass with 3 pointers.
1. low pointer = 0 , this check all the entries before it are 0
2. mid pointer = 0, this will be used to iterate the array
3. high pointer = array length -1, this checkk all the entries after it are 2.

- Now, we will iterate the array and check if the element is 0 then swap with low pointer and increment both low pointer and mid pointer.
- If the element is 1 just increment the mid pointer
- if the element is 2 swap with high pointer and decrement high but do not increment mid.( This is because if the number swapped from high pointer was 0 then we need to re swap it with low pointer).


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Take 3 Pointers low = 0, mid = 0 and high = nums.length -1;
- Use loop to iterate the array with condition mid <= high.(Since we only need to check middle elements of low and high).
- if element is 0 swap with low and low++, mid++.
- if element is 1 then mid++.
- if element is 2 then swap with high and high--.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Linear O(N), here N is number of elements in the array.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
Constant O(1).

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public void sortColors(int[] nums) {
        int low = 0, mid = 0, high = nums.length-1;

        while(mid <= high){
            if(nums[mid] == 0 ){
                //swap with left
                swap(nums,low, mid );
                low++;
                mid++;
            }else if(nums[mid] == 2){
                swap(nums, mid, high);
                high--;
            }else{
                mid++;
            }
        }
    }

    public static void swap(int[] nums, int i, int j){
        int temp = nums[i];
        nums[i] = nums[j];
        nums[j] = temp;
    }
}
```

