class Solution {
    public void sortColors(int[] nums) {
        int p0 = 0, p1 = 0, p2 = 0;
        for (int num : nums) {
            nums[p2++] = 2;
            if (num < 2) nums[p1++] = 1;
            if (num < 1) nums[p0++] = 0;
        }
    }
}
```

Quick eplaination:
* We always increase pointer p2 because no matter what value we're facing, p2 will go up. **Reason:** if `num == 2` when we must add a new 2, which means p2 goes up. Otherwise, we must add a `0` or a `1` which push p2 to the right, meaning p2 goes up.
* If value we're facing is 0 or 1 (<2), p1 will go up. So increase it.
* Only increase pointer p0 when we see a 0.

