# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The given Solution class provides a method sortColors that sorts an array containing 0s, 1s, and 2s. The problem is commonly known as the "Dutch National Flag" problem. The goal is to sort the array in-place such that all 0s come before all 1s, and all 1s come before all 2s.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The solution uses the Dutch National Flag algorithm, which is an efficient method to sort an array with three distinct values (0, 1, and 2). The algorithm uses three pointers: start, mid, and end. The start pointer points to the position where the next 0 should be placed, the mid pointer traverses the array, and the end pointer points to the position where the next 2 should be placed. The algorithm follows these steps:

Initialize start, mid, and end pointers to the beginning, the beginning, and the end of the array, respectively.
While the mid pointer is less than or equal to the end pointer:
If the element at mid is 0, swap the elements at start and mid, increment both start and mid pointers.
If the element at mid is 1, just increment the mid pointer.
If the element at mid is 2, swap the elements at mid and end, decrement the end pointer.
The above steps ensure that all 0s move to the left side of the array, all 2s move to the right side of the array, and all 1s are automatically placed in the middle.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the sortColors method is O(n), where n is the number of elements in the array. The algorithm traverses the array once, and each element is visited at most twice during the swapping operations.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of the sortColors method is O(1) because it sorts the array in-place without using any additional data structures. The sorting is done by swapping elements within the input array, and the number of extra variables used for the algorithm remains constant, irrespective of the size of the input array.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public void sortColors(int[] nums) 
    {
        int start = 0;
        int mid = 0;
        int end = nums.length - 1;

        while (mid <= end) {

            switch (nums[mid]) {
            case 0:
                // Swap with start index
                swap(nums, start, mid);
                mid++;
                start++;
                break;

            case 1:
                mid++;
                break;

            case 2:
                // Swap with end index
                swap(nums, mid, end);
                end--;
                break;
      }
    }
    }

    private void swap(int[] arr, int pos1, int pos2) {
    int temp = arr[pos1];
    arr[pos1] = arr[pos2];
    arr[pos2] = temp;
    }

}
