solutions.content:
A simple and fairly easy solution that requires three pointers which holds the number of 0's, 1's and 2's since these are the only visible elements in the array we can count them and increment the respective pointers using if/else or switch cases and the iterate over the same array again and fill it up accordingly with the count from the pointers. 

More explaination in the code inline

```
		int zeros = 0;
        int ones = 0;
        int twos = 0;

		//Count the number of 0's, 1's and 2's that appear in the array.
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++)
        {
            if(nums[i] == 0)
                zeros++;
            else if(nums[i] == 1)
                ones++;
            else if(nums[i] == 2)
                twos++;
        }

		//Now fill up the array with the information from the previous computation.
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++ )
        {
			//Exhaust all 0's first
            if(zeros != 0)
            {
                nums[i] = 0;
                zeros--;
            }
			//Exhaust all 1's once all 0's have been exhausted
            else if(ones != 0)
            {
                nums[i] = 1;
                ones--;
            }
			//Exhaust all 2's at last
            else
            {
                nums[i] = 2;
                twos--;
            }
        }
```

If you look this would be a O(2N) time complexity since we are making two passes.
1. To calculate the number of 0's, 1's and 2's
2. To fill up the array with the calculated number of 0's,1's and 2's.

A better approach to this problem would be using the **Dutch Flag Algorithm**

The solution to this algorithm will require 3 pointers to iterate throughout the array, swapping the necessary elements.

1. Create a low pointer at the beginning of the array and a high pointer at the end of the array.
2. Create a mid pointer that starts at the beginning of the array and iterates through each element.
3. **If the element at arr[mid] is a 2, then swap arr[mid] and arr[high] and decrease the high pointer by 1.**
4. **If the element at arr[mid] is a 0, then swap arr[mid] and arr[low] and increase the low and mid pointers by 1.**
5. **If the element at arr[mid] is a 1, don't swap anything and just increase the mid pointer by 1.**

Everything highlighted in **bold** are three important assumptions to follow above.

After the entire array is sorted  the thing to look is that high pointer will always be at the start of all 2's and mid pointer, low pointer will always be at the end of 1's and 0's.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/0a94332d-f419-418d-84ad-a8714ed39eb0_1655071660.3559823.jpeg)

Okay enough talk now lets look at the code -

```
    public void sortColors(int[] nums) 
    {

        //Dutch national flag algorithm

        int low = 0;
        int mid = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1; 

        while(mid<=high)
        {
            if(nums[mid] == 0)
                swap(mid++,low++,nums);
            else if(nums[mid] == 1)
                mid++;
            else
                swap(mid,high--,nums);
        }
    }

    private void swap(int a , int b, int[] nums)
    {
        //Neat little code to quickly swap without using the third variable and in one line.
        nums[b] = (nums[a] + nums[b]) - (nums[a] = nums[b]);
    }
```

