solutions.content:
Loop Invariant Explaination:
http://www.cs.cornell.edu/courses/cs2112/2015fa/lectures/lec_loopinv/index.html

For this question:
1. Establishment: The final answer must present in index [0, length - 1].
2. Preservation: 
	- mid point situation: val < num. mid + 1 point situation: bigger val, smaller num, at least same H. We can ensure answer will present in [mid + 1, right]
	- mid point situation: val > num. mid - 1 point situation: smaller val, bigger num, at least same H. We can ensure answer will present in [left, mid - 1].
	- Thus: Loop invariance is preserved.

3. Post-condition: The only situation we can exit the loop is left > right. The only situation we have left > right is when left == mid and val > num. We know we have the loop invariance, answer is in [left, right] in every loop. Thus, after right = mid - 1 = left - 1, left is the only point that is still valid as an answer. Then, return size - left. 

```
public int hIndex(int[] citations) {

        // corner case
        if (citations == null || citations.length == 0) return 0;

        int size = citations.length;

		// establishment
        int left = 0, right = size - 1;

        while (left <= right) {

            int mid = (right - left) / 2 + left;
            int val = citations[mid];
            int num = size - mid;

			// preservation
            if (val < num) {
                left = mid + 1;
            } else if (val > num) {
                right = mid - 1;
            } else {
                return num;
            }
        }

		// postcondition
        return size - left;
    }
```

